    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so like, who actually holds onto the money while it's sitting there? is it just a bank or someone else?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The entity that holds the money in escrow is typically a licensed real estate lawyer or a specialized trust company, not just any random bank. They act as the neutral custodian, holding the funds in a designated escrow account. This is a very important distinction, as these professionals are legally bound to manage those funds strictly according to the terms of the purchase agreement. They are the gatekeepers, ensuring the money doesn't get siphoned off by any of the involved parties before the deal is finalized.",
